# 6. Experimental Validation

H through N are the PA3 tests.
O through T are the PA4 tests.

## 6.1 VM and Replacement Baseline

- H: basic page-fault and vmstats sanity
- I: reference-bit behavior under pressure
- J: replacement and swap-in correctness
- K: scheduler-aware behavior under mixed priorities
- L: repeated swap stress with integrity checks
- M: vmstats syscall correctness/isolation
- N: forced eviction beyond frame limit

## 6.2 PA4-Specific Disk and RAID Tests

- O: strict syscall validation for setdisksched/setraidmode
- P: full-page byte integrity in RAID 0/1/5, including mode switching
- Q: exact eviction boundary checks
- R: fork correctness with swapped-out pages
- S: repeated evict/restore cycle correctness
- T: disk failure and recovery behavior (RAID 1 and RAID 5)

## 6.3 Running Tests

Build and run:

make qemu

Inside xv6 shell, run tests one by one:

H
I
J
K
L
M
N
O
P
Q
R
S
T

Automation helper:

- run_tests.py currently runs H through N.
- O through T are the PA4 disk and RAID checks.

Data-flow behavior validated by tests:

- Swap-out path validation:
  tests N and Q show evictions and swapped_out increasing under pressure.
- Swap-in path validation:
  tests L, N, and S show data survives and swapped_in increases on re-access.
- Scheduler path validation:
  test O switches FCFS and SSTF.
- RAID path validation:
  tests P and T check integrity and recovery across RAID modes and disk failures.

---

# 7. Design Decisions and Assumptions

## Design Decisions

- Swap pages are transferred in page-sized chunks as 4 disk blocks.
- Disk scheduling stays as a separate queue layer, so policy behavior is easy
  to observe.
- Swap slots record the RAID mode at write time, so swap-in uses the same
  mapping even after a mode change.
- Scheduler awareness is kept by using process level information from PA2.

## Assumptions

- RAID 1 and RAID 5 tests expect one failed disk.
- Multiple disk failures may panic in RAID 5 paths.
- Average latency is computed over completed scheduler requests.

---

# 8. Summary

This PA4 implementation adds:

- disk-backed swap
- configurable disk scheduling (FCFS/SSTF)
- RAID-backed swap mapping (0/1/5)
- failure simulation support
- extended VM + disk statistics

The result is a full data path for swapped pages:

VM page -> scheduler queue -> RAID mapping -> disk

and back:

disk -> RAID read/reconstruct -> scheduler completion -> VM remap.

The O-T test suite checks this path for correctness, performance, and fault
handling.

